posts.name: Yair Kornblau
posts.cooked:
trashgoblin:

Any chance you could talk a bit about your timeline (eg. how long CAD took, when was the robot built and fully wired)? Any struggles with one subsystem more than the others?

Our usual timeline is something like this(day count such that kickoff is day 0, week after is week 1): Week1: Day 0-1: “Spec” list is done - the main features / requirements we want to focus on based on our assessment of game strategy. Day 1(afternoon): 1-2 main robot concepts are drawn, including a list of initial prototypes to test mechanisms/choose between robot concepts. [this year, whether or not we could ground intake mattered a lot in the concept]. Days 2-5: pure prototyping, based on concepts suggested on day 1 and also OA / RI3D /whatever we come up with during the week. Day 6: CAD starts, usually when things are not yet fully baked but we have decided on a base concepts that we like. [This year the intake was far from finished and we had doubts about it working, but decided to stick with it and continue prototyping while CADing the chassis, elevator, arm and vacuum pump. Prototypes on the intake continued well into week 2, with us settling on final measurements around day 10-12. Same with the vacuum cup itself] Week 2: CAD and prototypes, usually one influences the other during the week [for example, the climb was designed based on the space in the robot, then it was prototyped, changed and prototyped again, all while CADing the final version]. Day 14: CAD is finished. [this year we took two more days for the intake, mostly components that do not influence the rest of the robot. We prioritized finishing the intake parts that do influence other stuff first so we can start making the rest of the robot]. Week 3: Fabrication + start of assembly of our practice robot. Usually we find some mistakes in that first robot build so we fix what’s necessary for the practice robot and make iterations for the comp bot. Week 4: Finish assembly + wiring. The deadline is day 28(end of week 4), but we usually finish before that. This is also usually the time when we start a “diet” for our robots [this year we had to find 3kgs around the entire thing] . Week 5: Software week, with the beginning of comp bot’s fabrication at the end of the week, once we’ve learned the big lessons from code/drive practice. Week 6: By the end of week 6 we strive to finish assembly and wiring on the comp bot. We walk into the process with all the lessons learned from the practice bot and with extra care to make everything perfect. At the same time driver practice and software are the main focus of the practice bot. [This year we made several iterations on the intake geometry + vacuum cup during weeks 5-7, and smaller changes during comp season.]

The entire process prioritizes software time + driver practice, as we usually implement some pretty sophisticated stuff at our first events. This year the intake and suction cup were the main development focus for most of the season, which is fine since they’re external to the rest of the robot.

posts.name: yotam manash
posts.cooked:
I don’t know the exact number of iterations, but I guess it’s around 10. Through each iteration, we looked for the best solution while keeping the geometry as simple as possible.

At the start of the process, we used one bottom axis of compliant 2-inch wheels (which later changed to a vulcanized rubber roller). For the top, we used 4 lines of 2-inch compliant wheels. It didn’t work very well because we didn’t have enough flexibility as needed for the coral. Throughout the process, most of the changes were minor adjustments to the position of the wheels and modifications to their size. The biggest change we made was switching to compliant stars instead of the compliant wheels. We found that the compliant stars are great because they provide the most flexibility for the least space.

That is pretty much how the process looked; if you have any other questions, let us know!
